        "upstream": "Identity & Access",
        "downstream": "Loan Origination",
        "relationship": "Conformist — Loan Origination conforms to the IAM system's user/actor identity model. Actor ID is embedded in every command and event."
      }
    ]
  },

  "trade_offs": [
    {
      "decision": "Use event sourcing as the primary persistence model instead of adding an audit log table alongside the existing mutable table",
      "gains": "Audit trail is the data model — impossible to have state without history. Point-in-time reconstruction is trivial (replay to timestamp). Immutability is structural. Captures intent (why a change was made), not just state diffs.",
      "sacrifices": "Significantly higher implementation complexity. Team must learn event sourcing and CQRS patterns. Simple queries that were one SQL statement now require maintaining read model projections. Event schema evolution requires careful versioning strategy.",
      "alternatives_considered": [
        "Temporal tables (SQL:2011 / system-versioned tables) — much simpler, captures row-level history automatically, supports point-in-time queries via AS OF. However: does not capture intent/reason for changes, harder to capture field-level granularity, and immutability depends on DBA discipline rather than architectural guarantees.",
        "Append-only audit log table alongside mutable loan table — simplest to implement, but audit log can diverge from actual state (bugs, missed triggers), reconstruction requires joining audit entries, and it's a bolt-on rather than structural guarantee.",
        "Change Data Capture (CDC) via database log — captures all changes at the database level, but loses business intent, requires infrastructure (Debezium, etc.), and raw CDC events are low-level row changes, not domain events."
      ]
    },
    {
      "decision": "CQRS with separate read model projections",
      "gains": "Read models can be optimized for specific query patterns (compliance queries, UI queries, reporting). Each projection can be rebuilt independently. Write model stays clean and focused on invariants.",
      "sacrifices": "Eventual consistency between writes and reads — users may not immediately see their changes. Infrastructure complexity of event subscription and projection management. Must handle projection failures and replays.",
      "alternatives_considered": [
        "Synchronous read model updates in the same transaction — eliminates eventual consistency but couples write and read paths, reducing resilience and scalability."
      ]
    },
    {
      "decision": "Snapshot store for performance optimization",
      "gains": "Avoids replaying potentially thousands of events for long-lived loan applications. Reduces aggregate load time from O(n) events to O(1) snapshot + O(recent events).",
      "sacrifices": "Additional storage and snapshot management logic. Snapshots can become stale if event schema evolves. Adds a component that must be correctly implemented to avoid subtle bugs.",
      "alternatives_considered": [
        "No snapshots, always replay full stream — simpler but may become a performance problem for loan applications with hundreds of events over their lifecycle."
      ]
    }
